column5: These peaks closely match those in the reference
These peaks closely match those in the reference
The peaks in spectra from isopropanol agree (± 4 cm−1) with published literature, except for the peak at 1,453 cm−1, which was 8 cm−1 away from the published reference (1,461 cm−1)

The peaks in spectra from ethanol closely matched those reported in the literature (± 4 cm−1)  [doi: 10.1002/jrs.6066], except for the 1,453 cm−1 peak, which was 7 cm−1 away from the published reference (1,446 cm−1).

The peaks in the spectrum collected from glycine matched the major ones for glycine (± 5 cm−1) reported in the literature [doi: 10.1016/j.icarus.2023.115769], though we couldn’t discern expected peaks with lower relative intensity. This might be due to our laser beam's comparatively lower power and focus versus the reference, which used 6.1 mW and a 50× objective.

Many peaks in the spectrum collected from L-methionine matched L-methionine literature [doi: 10.1016/j.vibspec.2012.12.004], however, not all of them do. We couldn't resolve the expected 659 cm−1, 1,029 cm−1, 1,338 cm−1, 1,363 cm−1, 1,451 cm−1, and 2,837 cm−1 peaks. This might be due to a combination of factors: our sample was powder instead of the more commonly used crystal, our spectral resolution was lower than the compared system, and we likely used a less powerful laser. Several of the peaks we did expect to see appeared as shoulders, likely due to the limited spectral resolution of our system. Surprisingly, we saw minor peaks that weren't in the reference spectrum at 1,072 cm−1, 1,177 cm−1, 1,494 cm−1, and 1,620 cm−1. While unconfirmed, these may be due to trace contamination.

The peaks in the spectrum collected from L-tyrosine between 1,100 and 1,600 cm−1 were in reasonable agreement with published literature [doi: https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.jpcc.6b10905], though it was challenging to resolve closely positioned or broader peaks. There were broad bumps in the spectrum, likely caused by several overlapping peaks at ~1,255 cm−1, ~1,430 cm−1, and ~1,530 cm−1. The spectrum had a lot of background fluorescence, but we recovered some peaks through baseline subtraction.

The peaks in the spectrum collected from citric acid up to 1,800 cm−1 were in close agreement (± 5 cm−1) with published literature [doi: 10.1366/12-06902]. The peaks above 2,900 are likely due to C-H and O-H stretching modes and have also been reported elsewhere [PhysicsOpenLab. (2022). Raman spectroscopy of minerals, crystals and inorganic salts. https://physicsopenlab.org/2022/05/11/raman-spectroscopy-of-minerals-crystals-and-inorganic-salts/].

The peaks in the spectrum collected from palmitic acid align well with published literature [doi: 10.1016/j.saa.2016.02.035]. They were also relatively easy to resolve, with little fluorescence background in this spectrum.

The peaks in the spectrum collected from glucose between 800 and 1,800 cm−1 were in close agreement (± 5 cm−1) with published literature [doi: 10.1016/j.snb.2016.05.151], except for the peak at 1,341, which was 7 cm−1 from the reference peak. We could not find a suitable reference for glucose in crystalline form that included the range beyond 1,800  cm−1, but we expect to see peaks due to C-H and O-H stretching vibrations in this region.

The peaks in the spectrum collected from sucrose between 1,000 and 1,800 cm−1 were in close agreement (± 4 cm−1) with published literature [doi: 10.1007/s12161-019-01598-1]. Below 1,000 cm−1 the fluorescence obscured Raman peaks, so we couldn't detect the expected 848 cm−1 peak. As with glucose, we couldn't find a suitable reference for sucrose in crystalline form that included the range beyond 1,800  cm−1, but we expect to see peaks due to C-H and O-H stretching vibrations in this region.
These peaks closely match those in the reference

Magnesium sulfate heptahydrate had a clear peak at 984 cm−1, more minor poorly resolved features between 1,050 and 1,200 cm−1, and a large feature in the O-H stretch region around 3,300 cm−1 that matches published literature [doi: 10.1016/j.gca.2006.05.022].

While we couldn’t find a reference for this exact compound in published literature, the major peaks at 978 and 1,068 agreed with a reference for a similar compound, Na2HPO4 [doi: 10.1023/A:1022803014898]. Together, these indicate the instrument allows the collection of accurate spectra comparable to those in the published literature.
